rman origin): habitational name from any of several places in Normandy or Picardy called Bray (Eure, Calvados, Aisne, Somme); see 6."],"variants":[{"name":"Dubray","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Napoleon.","French: habitational name, with fused preposition and definite article <i>du</i> ‘from the’, for someone from any of various minor places called Bray (see   Bray  ).","Altered form of French   Dubreuil  . This surname is common among Native Americans, namely the Cheyenne River Sioux in SD."]},{"name":"Braye","meanings":["English (Sussex): from the Middle English female personal name <i>Braye</i>. Its origin is unknown but it might derive from Breton <i>bregh</i> ‘fine, brave’."]},{"name":"Brais","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Aldea, Andre, Cecile, Fernande, Stephane.","French: altered form of   Bray  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":49,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":58,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":69,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":71,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":100,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Bray was born in 1500, in Camborne, Cornwall, England, his father, William Bray, was 14 and his mother, Margery, was 14. He married Margery Borlase about 1534, in Camborne, Cornwall, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1500–":"1500–Surnud","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1518–1570":"1518–1570","–1581":"–1581","1512–1556":"1512–1556","1535–1569":"1535–1569","1540–Male":"1540–Surnud","1546–Female":"1546–Surnud","1550–1614":"15